                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d564">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.01 Foreign Control/381: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Geneva (<persName corresp="#p_VSRG1" type="to"
                        >Gilbert</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-09-30T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >September 30, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>144. For <persName corresp="#p_RSJ1">Reber</persName>. After informing Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_FHSS1">Firestone</persName>, Senior, of your telegram
                    No. 274, <persName corresp="#p_HRG1">Howe</persName> stated that Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_FHSS1">Firestone</persName> said that the Finance Corporation
                    had no intention of considering “negotiating” unless and until the new annex 3
                    had been (1) fully accepted by Liberia, and (2) transmitted officially to the
                    Finance Corporation by the Department. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_FHSS1"
                        >Firestone</persName> added that he would inform his son to this effect.</p>
                <p>What will be the approximate date of arrival of the text by mail?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
